@Tim In a lot of places you can also get an em dash by typing two hyphens next to each other, just making sure there is no space on either side, and it’ll auto replace with an em dash—like this. 

That is the default on iPhone and most Microsoft products. Probably other places too. 

For an en dash in most Microsoft products, you can type a word or letter, space, hyphen, another word or letter, and another space. It’ll auto replace your hyphen with an en dash. That setting has actually been a frustrating default at work since it leads to a lot of en dashes where there should be em dashes.

